content: The description says it "works fine" on both phones and large tablets.  "Fine" is a gross exaggeration: on the Nexus 10, the graphics are herky-jerky and painfully low-res, and it only displays in a vertical orientation.  It's obvious that the developer was too lazy to actually upscale the graphical interface for tablets.  Better to go with DroidFish or some other free alternative - from what I understand, their engines are at least as strong as Shredder's anyway.

The developers must have updated the engine which is a good thing. It was susceptible to mating attacks involving extraordinary material or positional sacrifices. In my experience, the engine was vulnerable to this up to ELO 2100 settings. This gave me easy and short wins against levels 2000+. The weakness wasn't present in most desktop chessbase products (Hiarcs, Fritz etc.) so the change is quite welcome for this mobile app.

I've been searching for a menu as well. I emailed the dev and Stefan was very helpful. On the Samsung Galaxy S5 you push and hold the "recent apps" button (to the left of the home button) to reach the settings.  Regarding other devices, this is what Stefan had to say... "You need to press the menu key on your device to access the main menu in Shredder. If you device doesn't have a menu key you need to press or press and hold the button with the three dots in the ActionBar. If you do not have this button press or press and hold one of the buttons next to the home button or the home button on your device. Sometimes also a double tab on one of the buttons is needed. Often the menu appears by pressing and holding the home button or the button to view the recent apps for a while." Thanks, Stefan!

I play chess on the computer (Chess Master, Fritz, Deep Junior, Deep Aquarium with Rybka and Houdini, Arena, etc.) and with a dedicated electronic chess board similar to Mephistos and other chess apps from android including Ches Genius, Chess, etc.  I also play with the latest Pocket Fritz for the PDA.  And yet, the most fun I have is with this Shredder app.  I love that it automatically adapts to my strength (can be disable) and the board colors (specially the default) are beautiful.  There is a little "real time" measuring gauge on the screen that lets you know who is wining and it also tells you the strength at which it is currently playing. It comes with tactics/chess puzzles and the program is very customizable:  setup and analyze with shredder your own positions, import and export games, show analysis, keep screen on/off, manually set the strength, use clocks, coach, flip board, one tap input, setup time per game or per move... And... wait for it... it goes with me everywhere in my phone, ready when I'm ready!   HOWEVER, there are three things missing which I would love to see:  Chess 960, blind chess (few moves or whole game), and choosing custom colors for the board/peaces.
